The Project "Supporting skills acquisition and competences for students with intellectual disabilities" will be carried out by two special schools: Special Schools Group in Słupia near Kępno (Poland) and Bishopswood School in London (United Kingdom) for a period of 22 months.
These institutions are attended only by students with intellectual disabilities (mild, moderate or severe), who very often suffer from multiple disabilities (e.g. limb paralysis, hearing impairment, vision impairment, and many others). Our students face numerous educational challenges. The most recurrent problems are:
- an impaired ability to perform mathematical operations, e.g. instead of adding comes subtraction, and instead of multiplication - division;
- an inability to apply appropriate mathematical operations to real life situations;
- a lack of understanding of the relationships needed to perform mental calculations;
- a lack of understanding of relationships between numbers
- an inability to apply one's knowledge, e.g. mathematical operations which have been learned are not used in new situations;
- problems with the mastery of reading and writing.
The participants of the project will be students with various types of intellectual and physical disability and their teachers.
Through the project, on the one hand we will develop students' cognitive-social skills in difficult areas as described above, on the other hand we will - through the exchange of good practices - develop educators' skills and tools, so that they are more effective in helping our students with learning difficulties; in order for our students to effectively gain the skills and competencies they need for their present and future lives.
We aim to achieve these goals through activities implemented during the project: the participation of 16 employees and 44 students with their 30 carers during a week-long visit to the partner organization (activities related to learning / teaching / training).
In addition to the above activities, we will prepare an extensive project documentation, including curriculum and skills training based on learning by experience. The program will be open to use by educators from other special education institutions in the future. It will be made accessible by placing the materials in open educational resources, including the Erasmus+ Project Results Platform and in professional magazines / websites.

The project "Development of competences of the staff from King David Christian Primary School in the field of pedagogical and psychological help, methodology and mentoring of students" responds to the needs of our institution defined as a part of the European School Development Plan. Its main goals are:
1) improving the quality of teaching and revalidation of students with special educational needs,
2) broadening the competences of the staff in the field of teaching communication in Polish students who are initially non-Polish speaking students,
3) broadening the competences of the coaching staff to support students through in-depth mentoring. We want our teachers to pass the next stage of coach training so that they can develop the following students' skills:
- opening up, better communication and dialogue;
- implementation of complex projects, team work;
- free thinking, drawing conclusions;
- verbalizing, expressing your feelings, thoughts and desires;
- setting goals and accomplishing them persistenly.
The main activities of this project are: the participation in a job shadowing, a teaching assignment and a participation in the second-level courses in the field of coaching skills. Teachers, special pedagogues, Learning Support Assistants  and students' tutor-coaches who work in our school will take part in the activities mentioned above.
In the field of project management, the methodology of managing phases of the project life cycle will be applied, as well as methods inspired by good practices from other methodologies (PMI, PRINCE 2, TQM).
The project results include the accomplishment of all the goals described above, as well as the publication in open educational resources of descriptions of methods, tools, lessons plans, audiovisual materials with instructional activities and others. In the last phase of the project, various activities will be carried out to disseminate the hard results of the project. These activities will include training, webinars, sending e-mails, publishing information on available project results.
